Why do we need this? 
This drops boost::vector for std::vector by implementing a bmcweb::flat_map and bmcweb:flat_set?

Saves binary space;  Potentially could save some compile times because std::vector is simpler than boost.  Uses more std:: stuff, which is good in general.

I am good with this direction, I think the pros outweight the slightly harder code to understand (e.g. someone coming in and having to understand what bmcweb::flat_map is)

You moved to shared_ptr because in case in the future this gets shared with multiple objects / just simpler, we use shared_ptr a lot more?

"Unique_ptr is more efficient and expressive, but less flexible and compatible than shared_ptr."

I moved to shared_ptr because std::vector requires that objects are both copyable and movable.  If I'm honest, I couldn't really figure out why that's required (one would think you only need a move constructor).

When I compared to KVM and the other websockets that do the same thing, they used a shared_ptr and just made the whole thing copyable.

I'm fairly certain with a day of bashing my head at it, I could figure it out, but it didn't seem worth it for such a lightweight struct.
